rs are just starting to make their voices heard. But every woman who goes out and plays her music proves that "baring one's heart and soul takes courage, and Texas women artists have a lot of courage," as Lloyd Maines observes in the opening interview of this book. To pay tribute to these dedicated musicians and to capture their unique perspectives on what it means to be a woman in the music business, Kathleen Hudson has spent many years interviewing Texas women musicians for the Texas Heritage Music Foundation. In Women in Texas Music, Hudson lets us listen in on conversations with thirty-nine musical artists, including Emily Robison, Terri Hendrix, Lee Ann Womack, Rosie Flores, Betty Buckley, Marcia Ball, Lavelle White, and Bobbie Nelson. Hudson encourages and allows the women to tell their own stories as she delves into their life journeys, creative processes, and the importance of writing and performing music, be it blues, rock, country, folk, jazz, or pop. The interviews are warm and open, like good friends sharing the lessons that a life of playing music has taught them. What emerges from this collection is a solid sense of the strength and integrity that women bring to and gain from Texas music. Everyone who cares about music and culture in Texas will want to join the conversation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aPopular musiczTexasxHistory and criticism. 0aWomen musicianszTexasvInterviews. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aAbrahams, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlbert, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnnie, Rattlesnake, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBall, Marcia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeal, Neesie, econtributor.